As someone who drank himself nearly to death in his late 30s and early 40s, I will concur with the poster above that it’s not an effective solution to emotional problems. I eventually had to quit drinking entirely and am glad that I did. I don’t think every drunk needs to choose total abstinence, but years of failing to moderate my own drinking made it clear to me that I did.

I was slightly disappointed to notice that getting sober didn’t automatically fix all of my psychological and emotional problems. Alcohol numbed my emotions; getting sober forced me to actually feel and acknowledge them again, which felt a lot worse for a little while, but started me in a better direction. What ultimately helped me most was therapy, and being honest with myself and others (my wife most importantly in my case) about the fact that I wasn’t OK instead of pretending and hiding and seething/freaking out when I thought nobody was looking.

I also got some relief by changing careers and moving to a new place, but these aren’t necessarily realistic or appropriate for everyone who’s feeling shitty. Exercise, hobbies, distractions when things are acutely unpleasant in my head: all important tools as well. But none would have been enough all by itself and finding a combination of things to draw upon has been critical for me.
